or=1.\\n\\nSo the motor logic is:\\n- motor = vibrate_mode && ring\\n\\nNo wait, that doesn\'t match the requirements either. Let me think differently.\\n\\nWhat if the requirement is that:\\n- If in vibrate_mode, then motor = 1 (but only when ring = 1?) No that\'s not stated.\\n\\nThe correct interpretation from my own trace:\\n1. vibrate_mode = 1, ring = 0: motor = 0  (test expects this)\\n2. vibrate_mode = 1, ring = 1: motor = 1  (test expects this)\\n\\nThat means motor = vibrate_mode && ring. \\n\\nBut that seems wrong too because if vibrate_mode=1 and ring=0, we want motor=0, but that would make motor = 1 && 0 = 0, which is correct.\\n\\nActually, I need to check that. Maybe my implementation is right and I misunderstood which case is failing. \\n\\nNo, in the test failure log:\\nTime 30: vibrate_mode=1, ring=0 -> expected motor=0, got motor=1\\n\\nSo vibrate_mode=1, ring=0: my motor = vibrate_mode = 1. That\'s wrong.\\n\\nThe motor should be ON only if we\'re in vibrate_mode AND there is a ring.\\nThat is: motor = vibrate_mode && ring? No. Because then vibrate_mode=1, ring=1 would make motor=1, which is okay, but vibrate_mode=1, ring=0 would make motor=0, which is okay according to test.\\n\\nWait, but that doesn\'t make logical sense. It sounds like the intention might be:\\n- motor = vibrate_mode only when ring = 1\\n- motor = 0 when ring = 0 and vibrate_mode = 1\\n\\nLet me go back to basics and carefully interpret the spec.\\n\\nSpec says:\\n\\"If the phone is in vibrate mode (input vibrate_mode = 1), turn on the motor\\"\\n\\nSo: motor = vibrate_mode \\n\\nBut let me double-check how vibrate_mode is being tested in the stimulus.\\nLooking at the stimulus code:\\n```\\nrepeat(10) @(posedge clk)\\n    {vibrate_mode,ring} <= count++; \\n```\\n\\nSo count goes 0 to 9. That\'s binary:\\n0 = 00\\n1 = 01\\n2 = 10\\n3 = 11\\n4 = 100\\n5 = 101\\n6 = 110\\n7 = 111\\n8 = 1000\\n9 = 1001\\n\\nThis is: vibrate_mode = count[3], ring = count[0]. So:\\n0000: vibrate_mode=0, ring=0\\n0001: vibrate_mode=0, ring=1\\n0010: vibrate_mode=1, ring=0\\n0011: vibrate_mode=1, ring=1\\n\\nSo the case vibrate_mode=1, ring=0 (count=2) which results in motor=0 is valid.\\n\\nThis means I need to make my assignments to ensure that when vibrate_mode=1, motor is only on if ring=1. \\n\\nBut that\'s not really specified in the text! \\n\\nThe most reasonable interpretation is:\\n1. If vibrate_mode=1: turn on motor, turn off ringer\\n2. If vibrate_mode=0 and ring=1: turn on ringer, turn off motor\\n3. If vibrate_mode=0 and ring=0: turn off both\\n\\nThe key question is what happens in the second condition. Should it be exclusive between ringer and motor?\\n\\nLet\'s just try different combinations to match expectations.\\n\\nIf I follow the direct interpretation:\\n- ringer = !vibrate_mode && ring\\n- motor = vibrate_mode\\n\\nBut I\'m not getting the tests right. \\n\\nLet me try the opposite logic: \\n- ringer = ring && !vibrate_mode\\n- motor = vibrate_mode\\n\\nLet me try another approach. What if it\'s about the actual requirement:\\n- When vibrate_mode = 1: motor = 1 and ringer = 0 (vibrate mode overrides)\\n- When vibrate_mode = 0: only if ring=1 do we turn on ringer, otherwise both off\\n\\nSo:\\n- motor = vibrate_mode\\n- ringer = ring && !vibrate_mode\\n\\nChecking with test data:\\n1. vibrate_mode=0, ring=0: ringer=0, motor=0 ✓\\n2. vibrate_mode=0, ring=1: ringer=1, motor=0 ✓\\n3. vibrate_mode=1, ring=0: ringer=0, motor=1 ✗ Expected motor=0\\n4. vibrate_mode=1, ring=1: ringer=0, motor=1 ✓\\n\\nSo the third case fails. The motor is being turned on when vibrate_mode=1 regardless of ring. \\n\\nMaybe the spec doesn\'t literally mean: \\"Turn on motor when in vibrate mode\\", but rather:\\n\\"If in vibrate mode, then motor should be ON and ringer OFF (i.e., exclusive to ringing)\\"\\n\\nBut then it still doesn\'t make sense. \\n\\nLet me consider the simplest fix based on the failing pattern and trace through all four possible inputs:\\n\\nvib