de=1 -> expected ringer=0, motor=0 but got ringer=0, motor=1\\n\\nAccording to the specification:\\n- When vibrate_mode = 1, turn on the motor\\n- When vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 1, turn on the ringer\\n- When vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 0, turn off both\\n\\nLooking at the current RTL code:\\n```\\nassign ringer = (!vibrate_mode) && ring;\\nassign motor = vibrate_mode || (ring && !vibrate_mode);\\n```\\n\\nThe issue is with the motor assignment. When vibrate_mode=1, the motor should be 1 regardless of ring value, but when vibrate_mode=0 and ring=0, motor should be 0. \\n\\nLet me trace through what happens:\\n- When vibrate_mode=1: motor = 1 || (ring && 0) = 1 || 0 = 1 ✓\\n- When vibrate_mode=0 and ring=1: motor = 1 || (1 && 1) = 1 || 1 = 1 ✗ (should be 0)\\n- When vibrate_mode=0 and ring=0: motor = 1 || (0 && 1) = 1 || 0 = 1 ✗ (should be 0)\\n\\nThe motor assignment logic is wrong. The motor should only be on when vibrate_mode=1, and never when vibrate_mode=0 AND ring=1. But looking more closely, the requirement says \\"If the phone is in vibrate mode (input vibrate_mode = 1), turn on the motor\\" - meaning motor = vibrate_mode.\\n\\nBut wait, let me re-read the spec: \\"Whenever the phone needs to ring from an incoming call (input ring), your circuit must either turn on the ringer (output ringer = 1) or the motor (output motor = 1), but not both.\\"\\n\\nSo exactly one of ringer or motor should be high. This means:\\n- If vibrate_mode = 1: motor = 1, ringer = 0\\n- If vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 1: ringer = 1, motor = 0\\n- If vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 0: ringer = 0, motor = 0\\n\\nMy logic above was wrong in my analysis. Looking again at the test cases, when ring=1, vibrate_mode=0, the motor should be 0, but the current assignment gives motor=1 because of (ring && !vibrate_mode). \\n\\nThe correct logic should be:\\n- ringer = (!vibrate_mode) && ring\\n- motor = vibrate_mode\\n\\nWait, that\'s also wrong based on the first case. Let me look at this differentl